INSERT INTO quotes (philosopher_id, text, source, context, modern_interpretation) VALUES
(1, 'You have power over your mind - not outside events. Realize this, and you will find strength.', 'Meditations, Book 8', 'Written during the Marcomannic Wars while dealing with plague and military challenges', 'This encapsulates the dichotomy of control. In modern terms: focus on your response, not the situation. Your thoughts and reactions are your domain of power.'),
(1, 'The happiness of your life depends upon the quality of your thoughts.', 'Meditations, Book 4', 'Reflecting on the nature of wellbeing and mental states', 'Anticipates cognitive psychology by 1,800 years. Your interpretation of events, not the events themselves, determines your emotional state—the basis of CBT.'),
(1, 'Waste no more time arguing what a good man should be. Be one.', 'Meditations, Book 10', 'A call to action over philosophical debate', 'Philosophy without action is pointless. Stop overthinking and start doing. Character is built through action, not contemplation alone.'),
(1, 'If it is not right, do not do it. If it is not true, do not say it.', 'Meditations, Book 12', 'On moral discipline and speech', 'A simple test for ethical action: align your behavior with truth and justice. Before acting or speaking, apply this filter.'),
(1, 'The impediment to action advances action. What stands in the way becomes the way.', 'Meditations, Book 5', 'On turning obstacles into opportunities', 'Obstacles are not just inevitable—they''re essential for growth. What blocks your path teaches you how to overcome. The modern "growth mindset" concept.'),
(1, 'When you arise in the morning, think of what a precious privilege it is to be alive—to breathe, to think, to enjoy, to love.', 'Meditations, Book 2', 'Morning reflection and gratitude practice', 'Start each day with gratitude. Conscious appreciation of basic capacities increases life satisfaction—supported by positive psychology research.'),
(1, 'Very little is needed to make a happy life; it is all within yourself, in your way of thinking.', 'Meditations, Book 7', 'On the internal nature of happiness', 'Happiness is not found in external circumstances but in how you interpret and respond to them. Internal locus of control predicts wellbeing.'),
(1, 'It is not death that a man should fear, but he should fear never beginning to live.', 'Meditations, Book 12', 'On authentic living and wasted potential', 'The real tragedy is not mortality but never fully engaging with life. Memento mori should inspire action, not paralysis.'),
(1, 'The best revenge is to be unlike him who performed the injury.', 'Meditations, Book 6', 'On responding to wrongdoing', 'Don''t become what you hate. Maintain your character regardless of others'' behavior. Let virtue be your response to vice.'),
(1, 'Look well into thyself; there is a source of strength which will always spring up if thou wilt always look.', 'Meditations, Book 7', 'On inner resources and resilience', 'You have untapped inner reserves. Regular self-reflection and introspection reveal this strength. Modern: mindfulness builds psychological resilience.'),
(1, 'Accept the things to which fate binds you, and love the people with whom fate brings you together, but do so with all your heart.', 'Meditations, Book 6', 'On accepting circumstances while choosing attitude', 'Amor fati—love your fate. You cannot choose your circumstances but you can choose how you engage with them and with others.'),
(1, 'Everything we hear is an opinion, not a fact. Everything we see is a perspective, not the truth.', 'Meditations, Book 4', 'On the nature of perception and judgment', 'All observations are filtered through subjective lenses. Recognize that your interpretation is not objective reality—enabling cognitive flexibility.'),
(1, 'Confine yourself to the present.', 'Meditations, Book 7', 'On present-moment awareness', 'Past is memory, future is imagination. Only the present is real and actionable. Anxiety comes from future-focus, depression from past-focus.'),
(1, 'The universe is change; our life is what our thoughts make it.', 'Meditations, Book 4', 'On impermanence and cognitive control', 'Everything is in flux. The only constant is change. But you control how you think about these changes, which determines your experience.'),
(1, 'Do not act as if you had ten thousand years to live.', 'Meditations, Book 4', 'On mortality awareness and urgency', 'Memento mori. Time is finite. Act accordingly. Mortality awareness should focus priorities, not create despair.'),
(1, 'He who lives in harmony with himself lives in harmony with the universe.', 'Meditations, Book 4', 'On inner alignment and cosmic connection', 'Internal coherence creates external peace. Align your actions with your principles, and you align with the natural order.'),
(1, 'The first rule is to keep an untroubled spirit. The second is to look things in the face and know them for what they are.', 'Meditations, Book 8', 'On equanimity and clear perception', 'Two-step process: 1) Maintain inner calm, 2) See reality clearly. Neither blind optimism nor pessimism—clear-eyed acceptance.'),
(1, 'It never ceases to amaze me: we all love ourselves more than other people, but care more about their opinion than our own.', 'Meditations, Book 12', 'On seeking external validation', 'The paradox of caring: we prioritize our wellbeing but let others'' opinions control us. Self-approval should matter most.'),
(1, 'Begin each day by telling yourself: Today I shall be meeting with interference, ingratitude, insolence, disloyalty, ill-will, and selfishness.', 'Meditations, Book 2', 'On realistic expectations and preparedness', 'Negative visualization prevents disappointment. Expect difficulties, and you won''t be destabilized by them. Prepare mentally for adversity.'),
(1, 'Your days are numbered. Use them to throw open the windows of your soul to the sun. If you do not, the sun will soon set, and you with it.', 'Meditations, Book 2', 'On seizing opportunities for growth', 'Open yourself to experience and learning while you can. Don''t waste the time you have. Growth requires receptivity and action.'),
(1, 'To live each day as though one''s last, never flustered, never apathetic, never attitudinizing—here is perfection of character.', 'Meditations, Book 7', 'On the ideal approach to daily living', 'Balance: urgency without anxiety, presence without passivity, authenticity without performance. The ideal daily stance.'),
(1, 'How much more grievous are the consequences of anger than the causes of it.', 'Meditations, Book 11', 'On the destructive nature of anger', 'Anger damages you more than what angered you. The emotional reaction causes more suffering than the triggering event.'),
(1, 'The soul becomes dyed with the color of its thoughts.', 'Meditations, Book 5', 'On the formative power of thinking patterns', 'You become your thoughts. Habitual thought patterns shape character. Choose your mental diet carefully.'),
(1, 'Be tolerant with others and strict with yourself.', 'Meditations, Book 10', 'On differential standards for self and others', 'High standards for yourself, compassion for others. The opposite of hypocrisy: demand more of yourself than others.'),
(1, 'The object of life is not to be on the side of the majority, but to escape finding oneself in the ranks of the insane.', 'Meditations, Book 6', 'On independent judgment and sanity', 'Popular opinion is not truth. Think independently. Mass delusion is common—wisdom is rare. Maintain your rationality.');
INSERT INTO quotes (philosopher_id, text, source, context, modern_interpretation) VALUES
(2, 'We suffer more often in imagination than in reality.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 13', 'Advising Lucilius on anxiety and future fears', 'Most of what we worry about never happens. Anxiety is predominantly about imagined futures. Present reality is usually manageable.'),
(2, 'It is not that we have a short time to live, but that we waste a lot of it.', 'On the Shortness of Life', 'Essay on time management and priorities', 'Life isn''t short—we make it short by wasting time. How you spend your hours determines whether life feels long or short.'),
(2, 'Luck is what happens when preparation meets opportunity.', 'Letters from a Stoic', 'On success and readiness', 'What appears as luck is usually readiness meeting chance. Prepare yourself, and you''ll be positioned for opportunities.'),
(2, 'He who is brave is free.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 76', 'On courage and liberty', 'Courage liberates. Fear enslaves. Face your fears, and you gain freedom. Avoidance perpetuates bondage.'),
(2, 'Difficulties strengthen the mind, as labor does the body.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 13', 'On adversity as training', 'Challenges are mental exercise. Struggle builds capacity. Avoiding difficulty keeps you weak. Embrace resistance.'),
(2, 'Begin at once to live, and count each separate day as a separate life.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 101', 'On living fully in the present', 'Don''t wait to start living. Each day is a complete lifetime. Live it fully. Today is not preparation for tomorrow.'),
(2, 'True happiness is to enjoy the present, without anxious dependence upon the future.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 23', 'On present-moment contentment', 'Happiness exists now or not at all. Future-focus creates dependency and anxiety. Be here now.'),
(2, 'As is a tale, so is life: not how long it is, but how good it is, is what matters.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 77', 'On quality versus quantity of life', 'Length of life is less important than quality. A short meaningful life surpasses a long empty one. Focus on living well.'),
(2, 'The whole future lies in uncertainty: live immediately.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 101', 'On the unpredictability of the future', 'You cannot control what will be. Act now. Procrastination assumes unlimited time. You have only now.'),
(2, 'No man was ever wise by chance.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 76', 'On wisdom as deliberate practice', 'Wisdom requires intentional cultivation. It doesn''t happen accidentally. Study, practice, reflect—wisdom is built.'),
(2, 'If one does not know to which port one is sailing, no wind is favorable.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 71', 'On the importance of clear goals', 'Without direction, effort is wasted. Know what you''re working toward. Clarity of purpose makes action effective.'),
(2, 'It is the power of the mind to be unconquerable.', 'On the Firmness of the Wise Person', 'On mental resilience and strength', 'Your mind, properly trained, cannot be defeated. External forces cannot touch your core unless you permit it.'),
(2, 'Wealth is the slave of a wise man, the master of a fool.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 119', 'On the proper relationship with money', 'The wise use money as a tool. Fools are used by it. Money should serve your values, not control them.'),
(2, 'A gem cannot be polished without friction, nor a man perfected without trials.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 13', 'On adversity as refinement', 'Perfection requires resistance. Easy lives don''t build character. Friction creates polish. Trials create excellence.'),
(2, 'We are more often frightened than hurt; and we suffer more in imagination than in reality.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 13', 'On fear versus actual danger', 'Fear is usually disproportionate to danger. Imagined threats loom larger than real ones. Reality is often manageable.'),
(2, 'Wherever there is a human being, there is an opportunity for kindness.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 95', 'On universal opportunities for virtue', 'Every interaction is a chance to practice virtue. People are everywhere—so are opportunities for goodness.'),
(2, 'The mind that is anxious about future events is miserable.', 'Letters from a Stoic', 'On anxiety and future-focus', 'Future-anxiety creates present misery. You suffer twice: imagining future pain and experiencing present anxiety.'),
(2, 'Associate with people who are likely to improve you.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 7', 'On choosing relationships wisely', 'Your associates shape you. Choose people who elevate you. Proximity influences character. Be selective.'),
(2, 'Life is like a play: it''s not the length, but the excellence of the acting that matters.', 'Letters from a Stoic', 'On life as performance of virtue', 'Quality of character matters, not longevity. How you play your role is what counts. Excellence over duration.'),
(2, 'He suffers more than necessary, who suffers before it is necessary.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 98', 'On premature suffering through worry', 'Anticipatory suffering is optional suffering. Don''t experience pain before it arrives. Cross bridges when you reach them.'),
(2, 'The greatest obstacle to living is expectancy, which hangs upon tomorrow and loses today.', 'On the Shortness of Life', 'On future-focus robbing the present', 'Waiting for tomorrow kills today. Expectancy is a thief. Live now, not in perpetual preparation for later.'),
(2, 'You act like mortals in all that you fear, and like immortals in all that you desire.', 'On the Shortness of Life', 'On the paradox of human behavior', 'We fear as if we''ll die, but desire as if we''ll live forever. The opposite is wiser: bold action, modest desires.'),
(2, 'A great pilot can sail even when his canvas is torn.', 'Letters from a Stoic', 'On excellence despite imperfect conditions', 'Mastery means performing well with less-than-ideal circumstances. Don''t wait for perfect conditions. Navigate with what you have.'),
(2, 'Nothing, to my way of thinking, is a better proof of a well-ordered mind than a man''s ability to stop just where he is and pass some time in his own company.', 'Letters from a Stoic, Letter 2', 'On solitude and self-sufficiency', 'Comfortable solitude indicates inner richness. If you can''t be alone with yourself, something is wrong. Cultivate inner resources.'),
(2, 'You live as if you were destined to live forever, no thought of your frailty ever enters your head.', 'On the Shortness of Life', 'On denial of mortality', 'We live in denial of death, wasting time as if it''s infinite. Memento mori: remember you''re mortal. Act accordingly.');
INSERT INTO quotes (philosopher_id, text, source, context, modern_interpretation) VALUES
(3, 'It''s not what happens to you, but how you react to it that matters.', 'Enchiridion', 'The foundational principle of Stoic psychology', 'Events are neutral. Your interpretation and response give them meaning. This is the basis of cognitive therapy: thoughts, not events, create emotions.'),
(3, 'There is only one way to happiness and that is to cease worrying about things which are beyond the power of our will.', 'Discourses, Book 1', 'On the dichotomy of control', 'Stop trying to control the uncontrollable. Focus only on your will and responses. This single shift eliminates most suffering.'),
(3, 'First say to yourself what you would be; and then do what you have to do.', 'Discourses, Book 3', 'On intentional character development', 'Define your character goals, then align actions with them. Identity precedes action. Know who you want to be, then act accordingly.'),
(3, 'He is a wise man who does not grieve for the things which he has not, but rejoices for those which he has.', 'Enchiridion', 'On gratitude over lack', 'Wisdom is appreciating what is, not lamenting what isn''t. Gratitude for presence beats regret for absence.'),
(3, 'Wealth consists not in having great possessions, but in having few wants.', 'Discourses', 'On true wealth and contentment', 'Richness is low desire, not high possession. Reduce wants rather than increasing belongings. Contentment is internal.'),
(3, 'If you want to improve, be content to be thought foolish and stupid.', 'Enchiridion', 'On learning and ego', 'Growth requires abandoning the need to appear knowledgeable. Ego impedes learning. Accept being wrong to become right.'),
(3, 'Don''t explain your philosophy. Embody it.', 'Discourses', 'On action over words', 'Living philosophy beats discussing it. Actions speak. Words are cheap. Be the change, don''t just talk about it.'),
(3, 'No man is free who is not master of himself.', 'Discourses', 'On self-mastery as freedom', 'True freedom is self-control, not external liberty. Enslavement to your passions is the worst slavery. Master yourself.'),
(3, 'Any person capable of angering you becomes your master.', 'Enchiridion', 'On emotional control and power dynamics', 'If others can make you angry, they control you. Emotional reactivity is surrendered power. Maintain equanimity.'),
(3, 'Make the best use of what is in your power, and take the rest as it happens.', 'Discourses', 'On the dichotomy of control in action', 'Maximize what you control, accept what you don''t. Agency where possible, acceptance where necessary. This is wisdom.'),
(3, 'It is impossible for a man to learn what he thinks he already knows.', 'Discourses', 'On intellectual humility and learning', 'Certainty blocks growth. Empty your cup. Assumed knowledge prevents real learning. Maintain beginner''s mind.'),
(3, 'People are not disturbed by things, but by the views they take of them.', 'Enchiridion', 'Core cognitive principle', 'Reality is neutral; interpretation creates disturbance. Change your view, change your experience. This is CBT''s foundation.'),
(3, 'Demand not that events should happen as you wish; but wish them to happen as they do happen, and you will go on well.', 'Enchiridion', 'On acceptance and peace', 'Align your wishes with reality, not vice versa. Resistance creates suffering. Acceptance creates peace. Amor fati.'),
(3, 'The key is to keep company only with people who uplift you, whose presence calls forth your best.', 'Discourses', 'On choosing associations', 'Your companions shape you. Choose wisely. Associate with those who bring out your virtue. Environment influences character.'),
(3, 'Whoever then wishes to be free, let him neither wish for anything nor flee from anything that depends on others; otherwise he must be a slave.', 'Discourses, Book 4', 'On freedom and dependency', 'Freedom means desiring only what you control. Dependence on others'' actions or opinions enslaves. True liberty is internal.'),
(3, 'You are a little soul carrying around a corpse.', 'Discourses', 'On the relationship between soul and body', 'Distinguish self from body. You are consciousness, not flesh. The body is temporary housing. Mind your mind.'),
(3, 'When you are offended at any man''s fault, turn to yourself and study your own failings. Then you will forget your anger.', 'Discourses', 'On managing anger through self-examination', 'Others'' faults trigger anger. But examining your own faults generates humility and forgiveness. Self-awareness dissolves resentment.'),
(3, 'Know, first, who you are, and then adorn yourself accordingly.', 'Discourses', 'On authentic self-expression', 'Understand your nature before trying to present yourself. Authenticity requires self-knowledge. Be true to your nature.'),
(3, 'Circumstances don''t make the man, they only reveal him to himself.', 'Discourses', 'On adversity revealing character', 'Challenges don''t create character—they expose it. Difficult times show who you truly are. Adversity is the test.'),
(3, 'Freedom is the only worthy goal in life. It is won by disregarding things that lie beyond our control.', 'Discourses', 'On freedom through acceptance', 'Ultimate goal: liberation through letting go. Relinquish control over externals. Freedom comes from within.'),
(3, 'We have two ears and one mouth so that we can listen twice as much as we speak.', 'Discourses', 'On listening over speaking', 'Listen more, speak less. Learning requires listening. Wisdom comes through receiving, not transmitting. Shut up and listen.'),
(3, 'To accuse others for one''s own misfortunes is a sign of want of education. To accuse oneself shows that one''s education has begun.', 'Enchiridion', 'On personal responsibility', 'Blaming others is ignorance. Self-accountability is wisdom''s beginning. Own your responses and outcomes.'),
(3, 'Attach yourself to what is spiritually superior, regardless of what other people think or do.', 'Discourses', 'On pursuing virtue regardless of opinion', 'Follow what''s right, not what''s popular. Virtue over validation. Let excellence be your standard, not approval.'),
(3, 'Only the educated are free.', 'Discourses', 'On knowledge as liberation', 'Education liberates from ignorance, prejudice, and manipulation. Knowledge creates freedom. Stay learning.'),
(3, 'If anyone tells you that a certain person speaks ill of you, do not make excuses about what is said of you but answer, "He was ignorant of my other faults, else he would not have mentioned these alone."', 'Enchiridion', 'On handling criticism with humor', 'Don''t defend against criticism. Use humor and humility. Acknowledge your many faults. This disarms critics and maintains your peace.');
